@scottbelden thanks for working on this.  Using `hcltool <infile> <outfile>` against both the unix and dos/windows variants of a test file, results in the following JSON:

template file
```
resource "vault_generic_secret" "example" {
  path = "secret/foo"

  data_json = <<EOT
{
  "foo":   "bar",
  "pizza": "cheese"
}
EOT
}
```

HCL conversion to JSON (unix line endings):
```
{
    "resource": {
        "vault_generic_secret": {
            "example": {
                "data_json": "{\n  \"foo\":   \"bar\",\n  \"pizza\": \"cheese\"\n}",
                "path": "secret/foo"
            }
        }
    }
}
```

HCL conversion to JSON (DOS/Windows line endings):
```
{
    "resource": {
        "vault_generic_secret": {
            "example": {
                "data_json": "\n{\r\n  \"foo\":   \"bar\",\r\n  \"pizza\": \"cheese\"\r\n}\r",
                "path": "secret/foo"
            }
        }
    }
}
```

The JSON output is different, but that is to be expected as heredoc should capture whatever the line-ends are within the <<EOT...EOT herdoc construct.

My only complaint is that the code is prepending a `\n` at the beginning, and a `\r` at the end of the `data_json` field in the DOS/Windows example.

Instead of:
```                "data_json": "\n{\r\n  \"foo\":   \"bar\",\r\n  \"pizza\": \"cheese\"\r\n}\r",```
I would expect:
```                "data_json": "{\r\n  \"foo\":   \"bar\",\r\n  \"pizza\": \"cheese\"\r\n}",```

