@local-minimum we've a [nice guide](http://scikit-image.org/docs/dev/contribute.html) to facilitate new contributions.

Concerning masked arrays:
I think we need to work out some kind of specification on what should be the _correct_ use of masked array from both user and our points of view. I think, in `numpy` `masked` stands for `missing`.
At the same time, from my understanding, in image processing (as Josh said) missing data appears in several very specific cases:
- bad-pixels inpainting, sensors' butting gap correction;
- demosaic;
- segmented objects' manipulation;
- aftertouch, object removal.

Notice, that the meaning of mask is quite different across algorithms.
Saying this, there is not much sense to me to carry out masked array along the full processing pipeline. I think, it is much clearer to pass `mask` as an argument explicitly to those several functions, which may benefit from it (like, for example, [inpainting](https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/blob/master/skimage/restoration/inpaint.py#L75)).

